Optional Roleplay: The Pale Lady's Offer
If the party has dealt significant damage but hasn't finished the fight, or if they attempt to negotiate, the Pale Lady may speak:
The Pale Lady's Monologue:
 "Stop! Please... I was not always this. Once, I was Ismara Ice-Born, daughter of Jarl Yngvarr. I sought immortality to protect my people from the Dragon Cult. The ice spirits promised eternal life... but I did not understand the cost."
She gestures to her undead form.
"I am bound to this place, trapped between life and death. I cannot leave. I cannot rest. I can only... endure. The miners broke my seals. I did not want to hurt them, but my curse... it spreads. It hunts. I cannot control it."
Her voice breaks slightly.
"If you destroy me, the curse will end. The cold will recede. But I will be... truly gone. Not alive. Not undead. Just... nothing. Is there no other way?"
Player Options:
Option 1: Mercy Kill (Continue the Fight)
 The party can express sympathy but explain that she must be stopped. She accepts this with dignity: "Then make it swift. I have been cold for so long..." The fight continues, but she doesn't use Ice Storm againΓÇöshe's accepted her fate.
Option 2: Seek a Cure (Hard Guile or Magic Check)
 The party can attempt to convince her that they'll seek a way to break her curse without destroying her. This requires a Hard (-2) Guile or Magic check and a genuine plan (consulting the College, seeking Daedric intervention, etc.).
Success: The Pale Lady agrees to re-seal herself using her own magic, promising to wait while they seek a cure. The cold stops spreading immediately. This provides an alternative resolution and a potential future quest hook.
Failure: She doesn't believe them and attacks with renewed fury.
Option 3: Destruction (Standard Response)
 The party simply finishes the fight without negotiation.
GM Note: This roleplay moment is optional and depends on your table. If your players prefer straightforward heroic action, skip it and have the Pale Lady fight to the death. If they enjoy moral complexity, this moment adds depth.
