The Journal (Optional Lore)
If players read Ismara's journal, they learn her tragic story:
"I was a fool. The Dragon Cult marched on our hold, and I sought power to defend my people. The ice spirits offered immortality, strength beyond mortal limits. I accepted, thinking I could protect everyone forever.
But immortality is not life. It is the absence of death, which is not the same thing. I cannot eat, cannot sleep, cannot feel warmth or joy or love. I can only... exist. And worse, my curse spreads to those around me. The very people I wanted to protect, I now endanger.
The Greybeards came. They used the Voice to seal me here, protecting the world from my curse. I begged them to destroy me, but they said my death would release even more corruption. So here I remain, trapped on this throne, slowly freezing everything around me.
If you are reading this, I am either truly dead or you have found a way to end my suffering. Either way... thank you."

GM Guidance: The Importance of Treasure
Make Finding Treasure Feel Earned:
 Don't just list the itemsΓÇödescribe the party discovering them. Let them examine the war horn, try on the boots, read the journal. This is their reward for hours of gameplay. Give them time to appreciate it.
Let Players Discuss:
 After cataloging the treasure, pause. Let the party decide who gets what items. These conversations create memorable character moments and party dynamics.
Don't Rush the Resolution:
 This is the victory lap. The tension is over, the threat is ended. Let the party savor their success before moving to the epilogue.

